properties.description: The former studio home of the sculptor Dora Gordine and her husband the Hon. Richard Hare, a scholar of Russian art and literature. 1930s house over four floors including a flat roof terrace and views of Richmond Park.
properties.name: Dorich House Museum

properties.description: Fine example of an early 5-floor Queen Anne town house with original panelling, open staircase and unique 'swinging panels' on the open-plan first floor. Johnson compiled his famous 'Dictionary of the English Language' (1755)  here.

images.title: The Withdrawing Room at Dr Johnson's House
The stairs at Dr Johnson's House

properties.name: Dr Johnson's House

properties.description: Architecturally distinguished and well-preserved, brick-built, Elizabethan Grade I listed manor house. Contains 17C wall-paintings, wood panelling, a charming walled garden and a fine Tudor turret. Many original features have been restored.

images.title: Attic showing exposed timber frame of the property.

properties.name: Eastbury Manor House

properties.description: King's Cross is a 67 acre development in Central London being transformed into a new city quarter with 20 regenerated heritage buildings, new homes, offices, public spaces, shops, galleries, bars, restaurants, schools and a university.

images.title: The Coal Office and Canal Side Steps

properties.name: King's Cross Heritage, Energy Centre and Garden Tours

properties.description: Tiny polygonal building originally for the beadle. Used as local police station until 1930s and then as offices. Grade II listed.
properties.name: Old Vestry Offices Enfield

properties.description: Originally the studio home of Lord Leighton, President of the Royal Academy, the house is one of the most remarkable buildings of 19C. The museum houses an outstanding collection of high Victorian art, including works by Leighton himself.
properties.name: Leighton House Museum

properties.description: During the Open House Festival people will have the unique opportunity to explore the historic mansion that is the home of the Argentine Embassy in the UK. Opening its doors on this special occasion, visitors will enjoy unprecedented access to the home of Argentineans in the UK and explore a glimpse of our culture through an art exposition of different Argentine artists.

images.title: General Jose de San Martin. Argentine Ambassador's Residence

properties.name: Argentine Ambassador's Residence

properties.description:
Grade I listed Georgian church on the Thames. St Mary's has outstanding interior and monuments; commemorating those associated with the church: painter Turner, poet William Blake, botanist William Curtis and Benedict Arnold. 
St Mary's is hosting an Open House Week Floral Festival with arrangements and installations by local and international florists, as well as displays of historical documents.
properties.name: St Mary's Church, Battersea

properties.description: Built initially as a vestry, later extended. Victorian and Edwardian interiors with rich tiles and stunning stained glass, one of the most beautiful Victorian interiors in London.
properties.name: Chiswick Town Hall

properties.description: Founded by William the Conqueror's Archbishop Lanfranc in 1080 (the significant crypt survives) St Mary-le-Bow was rebuilt, notably by Wren after the Great Fire and by Laurence King in 1964 after WWII destruction. Home of Bow Bells.

images.title: Sanctuary and nave showing the hanging rood crucifix
The sanctuary; windows by John Hayward
Hanging Rood carved by Otto Irsara, a gift from the people of the Federal Republic of Germany
The current ring of 12 bells dates from 1961
The Blessed Virgin Mary depicted holding the church of St Mary-le-Bow, surrounded by other City churches and their patrons
Wren's Tower viewed from Bow Churchyard

properties.name: The City Churches: St Mary-le-Bow

properties.description: The independent cultural centre Pushkin House will contribute to this year's Open House Festival through a programme of events and community initiatives at its Grade-II listed building in Bloomsbury Square.

images.title: South facade on Bloomsbury Way. Photo by Dmitri Tsyrenshchikov
Music room. Photo by Dmitri Tsyrenshchikov

Pushkin House Bar. Photo by Dmitri Tsyrenshchikov
Pushkin House Bookshop. Photo by Dmitri Tsyrenshchikov

properties.description: Situated in one of the largest and grandest 19th century squares in London, 1 Belgrave Square was acquired by Romania in 1936 and is now home to the Romanian Cultural Institute.
properties.name: Romanian Cultural Institute

properties.description: St Anne's Church, Kew Green was consecrated in 1714. Built with the support of Queen Anne it has been a place of worship for the Royal Families over the centuries. The original 'chapel' has been extended many times and the church is now a little known gem in South West London with a fascinating past.
properties.name: St Anne's Church, Kew Green

properties.description: A cleverly integrated mixture of architectural styles and periods, incorporating a late 1720s house (later home to Herbert Henry Asquith) and the purpose-built College of Nursing (1926). Access to main building via guided tour only.

images.title: The front of 20 Cavendish Square today
Sign painting studio with Peter Liversidge

properties.name: Royal College of Nursing

properties.description: St Anne's Limehouse has been described as 'the finest parish church in England.' Designed by Nicholas Hawksmoor, it is Grade I listed and one of the Major Churches in the Church of England. It is home to a thriving Christian congregation.
properties.name: St Anne's Church, Limehouse

properties.description: The town's oldest firm of funeral directors has conducted funerals from these premises since 1908. The original interior is Grade II listed. The building also contains the Frederick W Paine Museum and the firm's archive.

images.title: Frederick Paine outside 24 London Road in 1913

properties.name: Frederick W Paine Funeral Directors

properties.description: Lesnes Abbey Woods is 88 hectares of ancient woodland, park and has a ruined Grade 11 list abbey ruin, situated 10 minutes walk from Abbey Wood train station. There is also The Clearing a new architect designed outdoor classroom.

images.title: Lesnes Abbey Ruins and Woods Credit Pilot Jonathan Potts Director Dagmar Scheibenreif
Lesnes Abbey Woods Credit Pilot Jonathan Potts Director Dagmar Scheibenreif

properties.name: Lesnes Abbey Tour

properties.description: The Gilbert & George Centre was originally established as a registered charity by the artist in 2009 with the objective to advance the education of the public in the arts, and generally to advance the arts, architecture, heritage and culture for the benefit of the public.

Main entrance gates - Photo by Prudence Cuming © The Gilbert & George Centre

properties.description: The King’s Cross Masterplan established a framework for the incremental redevelopment of this industrial heritage site through a mix of uses and a network of public spaces structuring new urban blocks and knitting the site into its context.

images.title: Granary Square at King's Cross. Courtesy of John Sturrock and Related Argent
Bagley Walk at King's Cross. Courtesy of John Sturrock and Related Argent

properties.name: King's Cross Masterplan

properties.description: An industrial building originally built for maintaining railways with a modern rear extension now housing a modern glass processing company
properties.name: Preedy Glass

properties.description: Medieval style church rebuilt by Sir George Gilbert Scott after 1867 fire. Tower & south porch are 15C. Large nave with open timber-work roof leads to chancel dominated by superb stained glass window & rich alabaster reredos.
properties.name: Croydon Minster

properties.description: Wren designed building of 1675, interior lost in blitz of 1940, reopened 1957 with 'Wren inspired' interior
properties.name: St Bride's Church, Fleet Street

properties.description: Come and see our CARBON NEUTRAL TERRACED HOUSE. Find out about our retrofit solar, batteries and air source heat pump installation. Double glazing, 20% increase in radiator size and roof / loft insulation. Flat roof and north facing roof all contribute.  Heat pump is ultra quiet and our old house is very warm in the depths of winter. Electricity bills still lower than gas.

images.title: Solar Panels view to the rear
Sofar inverter and distribution box in electricity cupboard
Pylontech 9.4 kw batteries in electricity cupboard
Vaillant 12kw Arotherm plus air source heat pump
100L buffer tank now in extra insulated waterproof box
Heat exchanger where gas boiler used to be
Purchased power from the grid 2023. Note the large contribution of solar panels April to October
Solar Export 2023. The house uses most of the energy from solar panels. This is the excess @ 8p/kwh
Solar generation, a typical summers day, cloud and sun. NB Good contribution by north facing panels

properties.name: 23 Sedgeford Road

properties.description: Our timber frame building was designed by Matrix Feminist Design Co-Operative, and built by women. It represents our community's history of activism - the same ethos that transformed our site from dereliction into a thriving community garden

images.title: Carpenter Louise Heaps working on the building's frame
Louise Heaps (lead carpenter, left) working on the portal frames for the building

properties.name: Walworth Garden

properties.description:
A great little museum set in the Grade 2 listed Ossulston Estate - a prime example of pre-war Social housing - based on Karl Marz Hof in Vienna.
Open Tuesday to Friday 9am-5pm, plus Saturday 14th, Saturday 21st and Sunday 22nd September 11am-4pm.

images.title: A museum on the social housing Ossulston Estate - a Space for us?
Pearly Queen outside the People's Museum
Hear the story of stolen social housing art from those who restituted it. Gilbert Bayes 'Draper'

properties.name: People's Museum Somers Town

properties.description: Around 35% of Londoners were born outside the UK - it’s  always been a city of immigrants and refugees. Hear the stories of the bankers, the builders, the child refugees and many others and their impact on the City for over 2000 years.

images.title: The City is a place of stories from different ages.

properties.name: Immigrant London

properties.description: A walk around historic Walthamstow showing how this unique area grew from a village into a thriving suburb, its social history and the variety of buildings that can be found where Epping Forest meets William Morris.
properties.name: From Forest to Morris: A walk around Walthamstow

properties.description: Square Root Soda will be running live production shifts to demonstrate how our drinks get made. You will be shown around our production space, where fruit will be being juiced and our other ingredients processed into our soda mix. Then you will be taken around our state-of-the-art packaging line. You will leave with an understanding of what the inner workings of a factory look like.

images.title: Inside the Square Root Factory - We Are Waltham Forest
Founder, Robyn, Inside the Square Root Factory - We Are Waltham Forest
Lemonade Production Inside the Square Root Factory - James Beeson
Rhubarb Production Inside the Square Root Factory - James Beeson

properties.name: Tour the Square Root Factory

properties.description: Poroban are offering free design surgeries throughout September online and at the studio where a range of sustainable materials and models are on display.  Poroban is a multi-disciplinary design studio, based off Old Kent Road, focusing on low carbon design including timber and demountable construction, maximising recycled/reclaimed materials and promoting a back-to-soil ethos to construction.
properties.name: Poroban studio

properties.description: Built in the 1950s, this site was originally the head offices for a large consortium of industrial spaces which produced dyes and food colourings. It is now a creative workspace with 26 studios for creative businesses and an event space.

images.title: View at night of entrance and neon signage
Ethical Colour exhibition by Colour of Saying
Ethical Colour exhibition by Colour of Saying

properties.name: Switchboard Studios

properties.description: Longfield Hall was built by William Minet and completed in 1889. It was designed by architect George Hubbard. William Minet also built the library opposite the hall, St James the Apostle Church on Knatchbull Road and much of the housing which surrounds Myatt’s Fields Park. Sadly the original library building was destroyed by a bomb during the Second World War, while Longfield Hall was undamaged.
properties.name: Longfield Hall

properties.description:
A 2.5 hour walking tour showcasing unexpected and hidden architectural landmarks of the South Bank area, revealing the different ways in which spaces have been reclaimed, reused and revived. 

Two guided walks held on two dates. The first walk follows a route starting from the Garden Museum, and the second walk starts from St John's Waterloo church.

images.title: County Hall. Photo by South Bank London
OXO Tower Wharf. Photo by South Bank London
National Theatre. Photo by South Bank London
Garden Museum. Photo by Garden Museum
Lambeth Palace Library.  Photo by Lambeth Palace Library
Feliks Topolski's studio in South Bank. Photo by South Bank London

properties.name: Lost & Hidden Architecture of South Bank Walk

properties.description: A floating acoustic architecture, playfully reframing public space as an essential community engagement through sound & site mapping. Accessed by smartphone, headphones & echoes.xyz app, the Pavilion is located outside the Serpentine Gallery,. Drawing on Oskar & Zofia Hansen’s Open Form architectural concept it is one of 15 in a series including Venice, Berlin, Dublin, Bergen and Arctic Norway.

images.title: Architectural and spatial design functions also as logo for London Pavilion audiowork
QR code to access London Open Form Pavilion of Air
Architectural design & spatial sound design for Pavilion with position in Kensington Gardens

properties.name: London Open Form Pavilion of Air

properties.description: Not many would believe that Notting Hill, now an extremely wealthy part of London, was once notorious for being a “slum”. This tour explores the stories behind the streets of Notting Hill and how their effects can be seen decades on.
properties.name: The traces that remain: stories from Notting Hill

properties.description: Tranquil Clerkenwell, so close to the bustling City has a distinct character and intriguing history. Once centred around great religious houses, the area has been the scene of fierce rebellion, innovative architecture, and major commerce.

images.title: Tudor splendour in the heart of London.

properties.name: Calamity and civility: contrasts in Clerkenwell

properties.description: Explore the Bush Theatre, West London’s home of new writing. Get a behind the scenes look at our fifty-year history, including how over 2016 we transformed our 128-year-old building into an accessible and sustainable modern theatre.

images.title: Daytime outside. credit 'Philip Vile for the Bush Theatre'
Bush Theatre outside terrace - Phillip Vile

properties.name: Bush Theatre - Backstage Tours

properties.description: See behind the scenes of SPACE's studio buildings that are not usually open to the public. Discover work by some of the UK’s top artists, from internationally acclaimed names to new and emerging talent.
properties.name: Belsham Street studios

properties.description: See behind the scenes of working studios that are not usually open to the public. Discover work by some of the UK’s top artists, from internationally acclaimed names to new and emerging talent.
properties.name: Deborah House studios

properties.description:
Walking tour: Sisters in the City

A walking tour celebrating the lives of women who’ve made their mark on the City of London over the centuries, from Boudicca to the Suffragettes
properties.name: Walking tour: Sisters in the City

properties.description: Home of NLA, London’s built environment community, and located in the West Wing of the Guildhall complex, the Centre highlights 3 scale architectural models of London: the New London Model, the City Model and the Royal Docks Model.

images.title: Model Talks at The London Centre.

properties.name: The London Centre

properties.description: Tour of our facilities. The tour will go through each section of our workshops, explaining each course and subject we teach in detail. Visitors will get a chance to view the workstations, tools, and projects our students undertake day to day at the college.

images.title: View from the mezzanine level looking down the workshop

properties.name: The Building Crafts College, Kennard Road, Stratford

properties.description: A great example of the rich evolution of London’s buildings; from noxious leather treatment warehouse complete with sloping floors, winch poles and loading platforms to a stylish hidden Art Collector’s Studio in the space of 150 years.

images.title: Anita Klein talking about her work to visitors to Eames Fine Art Collectors Studio

properties.name: Eames Fine Art

properties.description: A Grade II Listed building of special architectural and historic interest, it originated at the end of the 19th century, during which Walthamstow was transformed from a rural community to a bustling suburb of “London over the border".
properties.name: Walthamstow Central library

properties.description: We have been collecting objects about the history of Brent for over 50 years. Visitors can find out about an Eiffel tower in Wembley, why you might make a pilgrimage to Willesden and what the Victorian streets of Brent were really like.
properties.name: Brent Museum

properties.description: Sarabande was set up by the late designer, Lee Alexander McQueen, who left the majority of his estate to support creative and visionary talent.

images.title: Hannah Norton, photographer, Sarabande resident in her studio
Renata Brenha, designer (womenswear), Sarabande resident in her studio
George Richardson, sculptor, Sarabande resident in his studio

properties.name: Sarabande Foundation

properties.description:
•⁠  ⁠Drop in archival workshops

•⁠  ⁠Informal building tours 

•⁠  ⁠Free refreshments 

•⁠  ⁠Story sharing 


Discover more about the working lives of our landmark community building past, present and future. 


Meet our community producer and become  part of the Looking Out* story. 

*Looking Out is a Heritage England funded project celebrating working class histories.

images.title: An image from the Old Fire Station Archive
Visitors from our Looking Out! Project launch looking at archival images on the fire station walls.
Fire engine visit from our last open doors community event.

properties.name: The Old Fire Station Community Centre N16

properties.description: A pioneering virtual museum with a physical presence in London. We celebrate, research and record the richly diverse Jewish, refugee and wide migrant contribution to British visual culture since 1900.

images.title: The Hand Made Map of the World by Tam Joseph. Ben Uri Collection

properties.name: Ben Uri Gallery and Museum

properties.description: A series of events celebrating Croydon's Central Library building and its unique design. Croydon's first central library was moved to the Clocktower buildings when they first opened in May 1896. It was one of the first public libraries with open access shelves and offered one of the UK's first Children’s Libraries.
properties.name: Croydon Central Library

properties.description: Gubns partners with Of Architecture to host an open studio, pop-up and talk, showcasing a curated exhibition of works by architect-makers alongside a studio tour led by Of co-founders James Mak and Jongwon Na.
properties.name: Gubns Open Studio No.6: Of Architecture

properties.description: A walking tour exploring how the dockside of ‘the busiest port in the world’ has been repurposed but not destroyed to make a peaceful riverside enclave. Along the way we will discover some amazing spaces serving London in ways far beyond the imaginations of past Londoners and we will see evidence of current trends to reduce the carbon cost of redevelopment as London continues to change.

images.title: Luxury living where ships from all around the world once unloaded

properties.name: Renewal, reuse, refurbishment - a walk along Southwark's riverside

properties.description: Photographer Rachel Adams has been commissioned to create an exhibition capturing Croydon's iconic architecture & portraits of the people who look after these buildings, such as cleaners, concierge, security guards. The exhibition will be held here, at the Croydon Clocktower atrium & also at the Croydon Urban Room, located in the Whitgift Shopping Centre. For more information on visiting this exhibition at the Croydon Urban Room, head here: https://programme.openhouse.org.uk/listings/12687
properties.name: Croydon Unlocked

properties.description:
St Anne's Church, SW London landmark, nicknamed Pepperpot, is celebrating 200 years (Robert Smirke 1824). The church will be open September 16, 18 and 20 for guided tours, exhibits from the archives and entries from an Art Exhibition being held in August. There will be a talk by Gill Hedley, curator and writer, and the current church 
architect, Jodie Edwards, on the evening of September 19.
properties.name: St Anne's Church Wandsworth Bicentenary

properties.description: Come and discover work by some of the UK’s top artists – from internationally acclaimed names to new and emerging talent. See behind the scenes of a working studio, meet artists, photographers, designers, illustrators and all sorts of creative people face to face and buy works of art directly from their studio.
properties.name: Martello Street Artist Open Studios

properties.description: Come and discover work by some of the UK’s top artists – from internationally acclaimed names to new and emerging talent. See behind the scenes of a working studio, meet artists, photographers, designers, illustrators and all sorts of creative people face to face and buy works of art directly from their studio.
properties.name: The Triangle Artist Open Studios

properties.description: A chance to see behind the scenes of working artists' studios, this SPACE building is home to glass and lighting makers, ceramicists, fine artists and the London Embroidery Studio.
properties.name: Timber Wharf Artist Open Studios

properties.description: The walking tour will explore the showcase landscape and built environment of the Queen Elizabeth Olympic Park and its surroundings. The tour will showcase unique waterscapes in the area and talk about the importance of rainwater, water and sustainable urban design; its relation to public space and how water integration can shape and design spaces.

images.title: Wetlands Walk - Photo by Diogo Silvestre
Lea River - Photo by Diogo Silvestre
Glade walk - Photo by Diogo Silvestre

properties.name: Stratford's waterscapes

properties.description: Celebrating the NPG's architectural history and recent transformation by Jamie Fobert Architects, this architecture themed Late is designed to celebrate the building as a public space, highlighting the many connections to the built environment that the Gallery has – from contemporary design details that reference the local streetscape to the 400 portraits of architects in our collection.

images.title: The new entrance of National Portrait Gallery (Photography copyright Olivier Hess)

properties.name: National Portrait Gallery Architecture Late

properties.description: The Croydon Urban Room is a space to talk about the past, present and future of the Croydon town centre. Through conversa­tions, stories, exhibitions and events, the Urban Room brings together the views of those who live, work and visit the area to create a shared vision of the future and test new uses live in action.
properties.name: Croydon Urban Room

properties.description: Historic buildings and places are a treasure trove of narratives. How does our built environment, both old and new, contribute to our sense of belonging? Explore the studio and pop-up exhibition at conservation architects and heritage consultants Donald Insall Associates, which is within a Grade II-listed Edwardian townhouse, built in 1914 to the designs of Sydney Tatchell.
properties.name: Hidden Narratives: open studios at 12 Devonshire Street

properties.description:
Explore Christ Church, a Grade II George Baines art nouveau/gothic style church. 
Sat 14 Sept: 10am-3pm. Activities for families include a treasure trail, games and crafts and cream teas available. 2pm Lecture on George Baines by Andrew Wood, FREE.
Tues 17 Sept: 11am-1pm. Quiet space for prayer and reflection. 
Friday 20 Sept: 7-9.30pm. Concert with Life and mission choir, FREE
properties.name: Christ Church New Southgate and Friern Barnet

properties.description: Blackhorse Lane Ateliers is London's only craft jeans maker. Based within a tastefully renovated 1920s factory building in Walthamstow. Join us for a behind-the-scenes tour where you will get to see the factory in operation. Find out about our methods of production, the equipment, tools and materials we work with and meet some of our team.
properties.name: Blackhorse Lane Ateliers

properties.description: thinkFOUND make socially and environmentally sustainable furniture. We represent a social value model that gives back to communities around London. From our workshop in the Argall Industrial Estate we incorporate carpentry, fabrication, upcycling, training, employment, coaching and more. Over the weekend we will be hosting an open studio demonstrating our processes and showcasing past work.
properties.name: thinkFOUND

properties.description: Join us at our 13,000 square foot Grain workshop in Leyton to see British furniture manufacturing in action. Our entire collection is designed and made in our workshop. Come and see our contemporary dining tables, desks, stools and shelves – available in a large range of colours and sizes. Meet the designers and makers in our friendly team and find out more about what they do.
properties.name: Grain: Open Workshop

properties.description: Discover the work of innovative charity Furnishing Futures, which partners with the interiors industry to create trauma-informed healing homes for families given empty social housing after escaping domestic abuse. Enjoy a tour of our warehouse and studio, meet our team and learn about sustainability in interiors and the impact of trauma-informed design for recovery.
properties.name: Furnishing Futures Open Studio: Meet the charity

properties.description: Step inside the Climpson & Son's Coffee Roastery and see the inner workings of where your favourite coffee gets sourced and roasted.
properties.name: Climpson & Sons Coffee Roastery

properties.description: Join us for a special open day at Kribi Coffee UK! Owners Anne and Luca will guide you on a tour through the air roastery and share the rich story of Cameroonian coffee and their family’s connection to the farmers and the land. There will be live demonstrations of the coffee air roaster and some sample coffee to try!
properties.name: Kribi Coffee Roastery

properties.description: Guiding the development of a new urban centre at the heart of south-east London's Rotherhithe peninsula, historically a network of working docks and canals connected to the River Thames - and recently the home of a 1980s low density shopping centre. Sitting between two underground stations and two waterbodies, it offers the opportunity to create a characterful, well-connected London neighbourhood.
properties.name: Canada Water Masterplan

properties.description: Royal Arsenal Riverside is a place of rich history, long known by its link to Woolwich’s military origins dating back to the 16th c. Now in its third decade, the masterplan has set the design principles to help write its next chapter. Learn how this historic waterfront site has been transformed into a thriving and well-connect new neighbourhood through a guided walking tour by the masterplanners.
properties.name: Woolwich Arsenal Masterplan

properties.description: We are a theatre company for performers and artists with learning disabilities in the West London area.  We will screen a free immersive experience, run on a loop, entitled Red Rope. It tells a powerful story about the impact of plastic on our oceans and features artworks, dance, music and poetry by our performers and artists. We will also display works of art.

images.title: Red Rope immersive experience in our Studio Theatre

properties.name: IMPACT Community Arts Centre

properties.description: Up in Smoke - the NOW Gallery Design Commission by artist John Booth and architecture studio CAN, transforms the gallery into a vibrant installation that reveals the rich history of Greenwich Peninsula, through its iconic chimneys. The exhibition combines the duo's distinctive styles: Booth's playful, colourful design aesthetic and CAN's fresh, irreverent approach to architecture.
properties.name: Up in Smoke by John Booth X CAN

properties.description: Every hour on the hour Neckstamper will give a brewery tour explaining our brewing process and equipment we use. The brewery taproom will also be open for the public to enjoy our beer or purchase cans to take away.
properties.name: Neckstamper Brewery

properties.description: Alfies Antique Market is London's largest indoor antique and vintage market. The market celebrates 90 dealers who each boast uniquely sourced antique and vintage items.
properties.name: Alfies Antique Market

properties.description: Once a Victorian arboretum, Abney Park Cemetery, part of London's Magnificent Seven, was revitalised with National Heritage Lottery funding in 2021. The renovation restored the chapel and main entrance, creating a vibrant workshop space for London-based art and design collective, WAX Atelier. During Open House, WAX Atelier will showcase innovative projects in their unique workspace amidst the park

images.title: WAX Atelier's Materials Lab at Abney Park
CQ Studio's Material Lab at Abney Park

properties.name: WAX Atelier within Abney Park

properties.description: Interested in history, food and Victorian architecture?  This early morning tour (6.30am start) with a City Guide provides a perfect opportunity to experience the hustle and bustle of the City of London’s last surviving market at first hand.
properties.name: Smithfield Market Tour

properties.description: Nestled in the heart of West London, our establishment draws inspiration from the legendary Mount Toteil, celebrated for its rich history and cultural significance. Delight in our diverse menu, featuring authentic dishes that encapsulate the vibrant flavors and heritage of the region.
properties.name: Toteil Restaurant

properties.description: Ever wondered as you wandered what exactly led to that bench looking like that, why London's telephone boxes are red, what those green huts are, and why there are no public toilets anymore...? If 'YES!' then join us as we saunter around Temple / the Strand with these questions in mind, stopping to peek at parts of the city fabric that we often overlook - learning about the designers and deciders.
properties.name: Inbetween spaces - The Strand's public realm

properties.description: Come and explore the Isokon collection and workshop and learn more about our manufacturing processes. Experience the techniques and materials that are used to craft our collection which spans over 90 years of modernist and contemporary furniture design.

images.title: Bodliean Library Chair in production. Photograph by Sam Bush.
Penguin donkey maker in the Isokon workshop
Isokon Iso Lounge in production. Photograph by Nicola Tree.
Isokon Long Chair and Press. Photograph by Max Creasy.

properties.name: The Isokon Collection and Open Workshop
